The non-parametric Random Forest supervised image classification algorithm, a component of the R program, was used to classify the Landsat images [20]. The land use mapping technique is depicted in Fig. 2
                        . A collection of decision trees that are created autonomously by a machine learning algorithm called a random forest. A random collection of training samples (2/3) is used to create the tree of a random forest. The generalization mistakes linked to a single classification tree are overcome by increasing the number of trees during classification by increasing classification accuracy [20]. Based on the researcher's previous study and previous studies e.g. Refs. [18,21], of the study area, a classification system with five classes was implemented and modified: water bodies, cropland, open forest, settlement, and dense forest (Table 2
                        ). In this research, the algorithm was trained using high-resolution satellite images from Google Earth and ground truth data from a field campaign in 2019. Two-thirds of the training data are used for classification by the algorithm, and one-third of the leftover training samples are used for internal validation or accuracy evaluation.
